# Diagnostic Ruleset Matrix: WCAG 2.1 Level A

## Perceivable

### 1.1.1 Non-Text Content
All non-text content presented to the user must have a text alternative that serves the equivalent purpose.
- Identify all `<img>`, `<svg>`, `<canvas>`, `<video>`, `<audio>`, `<object>`, `<embed>`, and `<iframe>` elements lacking the `alt` attribute or accessible name.
- Differentiate between **meaningful imagery** requiring descriptive `alt` text and **decorative imagery** requiring `alt=""` combined with `aria-hidden="true"` or `role="presentation"`.
- Verify `<svg>` elements include either a `<title>` child element, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby` reference.
- Verify icon fonts or icon-only buttons provide `aria-label` or visually hidden text.
- Check that `<input type="image">` elements include a descriptive `alt` attribute.
- Verify CSS background images conveying meaning have a text alternative in the DOM.

### 1.2.1 Audio-only and Video-only (Prerecorded)
Prerecorded audio-only and video-only media must provide an alternative.
- Identify `<audio>` elements without an adjacent transcript link or `<track kind="descriptions">`.
- Identify `<video>` elements without audio tracks that lack a text transcript or audio description alternative.

### 1.2.2 Captions (Prerecorded)
Captions must be provided for all prerecorded audio content in synchronized media.
- Identify `<video>` elements that do not include a `<track kind="captions">` or `<track kind="subtitles">` child element.
- Verify caption tracks have a valid `src` attribute pointing to a `.vtt` or `.srt` file.

### 1.2.3 Audio Description or Media Alternative (Prerecorded)
An alternative for time-based media or audio description must be provided for prerecorded video content.
- Identify `<video>` elements missing both `<track kind="descriptions">` and an adjacent text transcript.

### 1.3.1 Info and Relationships
Information, structure, and relationships conveyed through presentation must be programmatically determinable.
- **Heading hierarchy**: Verify logical sequence — `<h2>` must follow `<h1>`, `<h3>` must follow `<h2>`, etc. Identify skipped heading levels (e.g., `<h1>` followed directly by `<h3>`). Identify multiple `<h1>` elements within a single view.
- **Form associations**: Verify every `<input>`, `<select>`, and `<textarea>` is programmatically linked to a `<label>` via matching `for`/`id` attributes, wrapping `<label>`, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby`.
- **Table structure**: Verify data tables use `<th>` elements with `scope="col"` or `scope="row"`. Identify layout tables that should use `role="presentation"` or `role="none"`.
- **List structure**: Verify list content uses `<ul>`, `<ol>`, or `<dl>` rather than styled `<div>`/`<span>` sequences. Identify `<li>` elements not wrapped in `<ul>` or `<ol>`.
- **Landmark regions**: Verify pages use semantic landmarks (`<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`) or equivalent ARIA roles. Identify pages missing a `<main>` landmark.
- **Fieldset/legend**: Verify grouped form controls (radio buttons, checkboxes) are wrapped in `<fieldset>` with a `<legend>`.

### 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence
The correct reading sequence can be programmatically determined when the sequence affects meaning.
- Identify CSS properties (`order`, `flex-direction: row-reverse`, `flex-direction: column-reverse`, `direction: rtl`, `float`, absolute/fixed positioning) that cause visual order to deviate from DOM source order in a way that could break meaning or reading flow.
- Verify tabindex values do not force a reading order different from visual order.

### 1.3.3 Sensory Characteristics
Instructions must not rely solely on sensory characteristics such as shape, color, size, visual location, orientation, or sound.
- Identify instructional text referencing position ("the button on the right"), shape ("the round icon"), color ("click the green button"), or size alone without additional non-sensory cues.

### 1.4.1 Use of Color
Color must not be the only visual means of conveying information, indicating an action, prompting a response, or distinguishing a visual element.
- Identify form validation that uses only color change (red border) without an icon, text message, or `aria-invalid` attribute.
- Identify links within body text distinguished only by color without underline, bold, or other non-color indicator.
- Identify charts or graphs that rely solely on color to differentiate data series without patterns, labels, or legends.

### 1.4.2 Audio Control
If audio plays automatically for more than 3 seconds, a mechanism must exist to pause, stop, or control volume independently.
- Identify `<audio autoplay>` or `<video autoplay>` elements. Verify a pause/stop mechanism exists and is keyboard accessible.

## Operable

### 2.1.1 Keyboard
All functionality must be operable through a keyboard interface without requiring specific timings for individual keystrokes.
- Identify interactive DOM nodes (`<div>`, `<span>`, `<a>` without `href`, custom elements) with `onClick`/`@click` handlers lacking `onKeyDown`/`onKeyUp`/`onKeyPress` keyboard handlers.
- Verify all custom interactive components implement appropriate keyboard patterns (Enter/Space for buttons, arrow keys for menus/tabs/tree views).
- Verify `tabindex` is never greater than `0`. Only `0` (document-order focusable) and `-1` (programmatically focusable) are permitted.
- Identify elements with `role="button"`, `role="link"`, `role="tab"`, or `role="menuitem"` that are not focusable (`tabindex="0"` or native focusable element).

### 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap
If keyboard focus can be moved to a component using a keyboard interface, focus must be movable away using only a keyboard interface.
- Identify modal dialogs, overlays, and popups that do not trap focus within the component or do not release focus back on close.
- Identify components that capture focus without providing an Escape key or documented mechanism to release.
- Verify modal dialogs implement proper focus trap (focus cycling within the modal) and return focus to the trigger element on close.

### 2.1.4 Character Key Shortcuts (WCAG 2.1)
If single character key shortcuts exist, they must be remappable, disableable, or only active when the relevant component has focus.
- Identify global keyboard event listeners (`document.addEventListener('keydown', ...)`) that trigger actions on single character keys (letters, numbers, punctuation) without modifier keys (Ctrl, Alt, Shift, Meta).

### 2.2.1 Timing Adjustable
If time limits are set by content, the user must be able to turn off, adjust, or extend the time limit.
- Identify `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, or `requestAnimationFrame` patterns driving auto-redirects, session timeouts, or content expiration without user notification or extension mechanism.
- Identify auto-advancing carousels or slideshows lacking pause controls.

### 2.2.2 Pause, Stop, Hide
For moving, blinking, scrolling, or auto-updating content, the user must be able to pause, stop, or hide it.
- Identify CSS animations (`animation`, `@keyframes`, `transition` running continuously) on content that starts automatically, lasts more than 5 seconds, and lacks a pause mechanism.
- Identify auto-scrolling tickers, marquees, or carousels without pause/stop controls.
- Verify respect for `prefers-reduced-motion` media query — animations should be reduced or disabled when the user prefers reduced motion.

### 2.3.1 Three Flashes or Below Threshold
Content must not flash more than three times in any one-second period.
- Identify CSS animations or JavaScript-driven visual effects that could produce rapid flashing (e.g., rapid `opacity` or `background-color` cycling with duration below 333ms).

### 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks
A mechanism must exist to bypass blocks of content repeated across multiple pages.
- Verify a "Skip to main content" link exists as the first focusable element on each page. The link must be visible on focus and target the `<main>` region or an `id` at the start of the primary content area.
- Verify landmark regions (`<nav>`, `<main>`, `<aside>`) are used to allow assistive technology navigation.

### 2.4.2 Page Titled
Web pages must have titles that describe topic or purpose.
- Verify each page/route has a descriptive `<title>` element (for SPAs, verify dynamic `document.title` updates on route changes).
- Identify pages with generic titles ("Untitled", "Page", empty string) or pages sharing identical titles across different views.

### 2.4.3 Focus Order
If content can be navigated sequentially and navigation sequences affect meaning or operation, focusable components must receive focus in an order that preserves meaning and operability.
- Identify positive `tabindex` values (`tabindex="2"`, `tabindex="5"`, etc.) that override natural DOM order.
- Verify that modal dialogs, drawers, and popovers move focus into the component when opened and return focus when closed.
- Identify dynamically inserted content that should receive focus but does not (e.g., inline error messages, expanded sections).

### 2.4.4 Link Purpose (In Context)
The purpose of each link must be determinable from the link text alone or from the link text together with its programmatically determined context.
- Identify links with generic text ("Click here", "Read more", "Learn more", "Here", "Link") without `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, or surrounding context that clarifies purpose.
- Identify empty links (`<a href="..."></a>`) or links containing only an icon without accessible text.

### 2.5.1 Pointer Gestures (WCAG 2.1)
Functionality operated via multipoint or path-based gestures must also be operable with a single pointer without a path-based gesture.
- Identify swipe-dependent carousels, pinch-to-zoom, or multi-finger gesture handlers that lack single-tap/click button alternatives (next/previous buttons, zoom controls).

### 2.5.2 Pointer Cancellation (WCAG 2.1)
For single-pointer functionality, at least one of the following must be true: no down-event, can abort/undo, up reversal.
- Identify `mousedown`, `touchstart`, or `pointerdown` event handlers that trigger irreversible actions without confirmation or undo. Actions should trigger on `mouseup`/`click`/`pointerup` instead.

### 2.5.3 Label in Name (WCAG 2.1)
For UI components with labels that include text or images of text, the accessible name must contain the text that is presented visually.
- Identify components where `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby` produces an accessible name that does not contain the visible label text (e.g., button visually reads "Submit Order" but `aria-label="Place"`) .
- Verify that `aria-label` on a button matches or contains the visible text on that button.

### 2.5.4 Motion Actuation (WCAG 2.1)
Functionality triggered by device motion (shake, tilt) must also be operable via UI controls and can be disabled.
- Identify `DeviceMotionEvent` or `DeviceOrientationEvent` listeners that trigger functionality without an equivalent on-screen control.

## Understandable

### 3.1.1 Language of Page
The default human language of each page must be programmatically determinable.
- Verify the `<html>` element includes a valid `lang` attribute (e.g., `lang="en"`, `lang="fr"`).
- Identify missing or empty `lang` attributes on the root `<html>` element.

### 3.2.1 On Focus
Receiving focus must not initiate a change of context.
- Identify `onfocus` or `onFocus` handlers that trigger navigation, form submission, or modal opening.

### 3.2.2 On Input
Changing the setting of any UI component must not automatically cause a change of context unless the user has been advised beforehand.
- Identify `<select>` elements with `onChange` handlers that trigger navigation or form submission without a separate submit button.
- Identify radio buttons or checkboxes that trigger page navigation on change.

### 3.3.1 Error Identification
If an input error is automatically detected, the item in error must be identified and the error described to the user in text.
- Identify form validation that only uses visual indicators (red border, color change) without text error messages.
- Verify error messages are programmatically associated with inputs via `aria-describedby`, `aria-errormessage`, or adjacent text.
- Verify `aria-invalid="true"` is set on inputs in an error state.

### 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions
Labels or instructions must be provided when content requires user input.
- Verify all form inputs have visible labels (not just placeholder text).
- Identify inputs relying solely on `placeholder` as the label — placeholders disappear on input and are insufficient.
- Verify required fields are indicated both visually and programmatically (`aria-required="true"` or `required` attribute).
- Verify expected format instructions are provided (e.g., "MM/DD/YYYY" for date fields).

## Robust

### 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value
For all UI components, the name, role, and state must be programmatically determinable; states/values must be settable by user agents and assistive technologies.
- Identify custom components (dropdowns, toggles, accordions, tabs, sliders) built from `<div>`/`<span>` without appropriate ARIA roles (`role="combobox"`, `role="switch"`, `role="tablist"`, `role="slider"`, etc.).
- Verify custom toggles/checkboxes communicate state via `aria-checked`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-selected`, or `aria-pressed`.
- Verify custom comboboxes/dropdowns use `aria-expanded`, `aria-haspopup`, and `aria-activedescendant` or equivalent.
- Identify duplicate `id` attributes in the DOM that could break label associations or ARIA references.

