# Diagnostic Ruleset Matrix: WCAG 2.1 Level AA

## Perceivable

### 1.2.4 Captions (Live)
Captions must be provided for all live audio content in synchronized media.
- Identify live video/audio streaming components without live captioning integration or instructions for enabling captions.

### 1.2.5 Audio Description (Prerecorded)
Audio description must be provided for all prerecorded video content in synchronized media.
- Identify `<video>` elements without `<track kind="descriptions">` and without an adjacent audio-described version link.

### 1.3.4 Orientation (WCAG 2.1)
Content must not restrict its view and operation to a single display orientation unless a specific orientation is essential.
- Identify CSS or JavaScript that locks the page to portrait or landscape mode (`orientation: portrait` in media queries enforced with no alternative, or `screen.orientation.lock()`).

### 1.3.5 Identify Input Purpose (WCAG 2.1)
The purpose of each input field collecting information about the user must be programmatically determinable.
- Identify `<input>` fields for personal data (name, email, phone, address, credit card, password) that lack the `autocomplete` attribute.
- Expected values: `name`, `given-name`, `family-name`, `email`, `tel`, `street-address`, `postal-code`, `country`, `cc-number`, `cc-exp`, `cc-csc`, `username`, `current-password`, `new-password`, `one-time-code`, `bday`, etc.

### 1.4.3 Contrast (Minimum)
Text and images of text must have a contrast ratio of at least 4.5:1 (3:1 for large text, 18pt+ or 14pt+ bold).
- Analyze foreground/background color combinations in CSS. Identify hardcoded color pairs falling below the 4.5:1 threshold for normal text or 3:1 for large text.
- Check text over gradient or image backgrounds — verify sufficient contrast at all points.
- Verify placeholder text meets contrast requirements (placeholders are often too light).
- Identify disabled elements — note that disabled controls are exempt from contrast requirements.

### 1.4.4 Resize Text
Text must be resizable up to 200% without loss of content or functionality.
- Identify text sized in absolute units (`px`) on `<body>` or root elements without `rem`/`em` equivalents.
- Identify `overflow: hidden` on containers that could clip text when zoomed.
- Identify fixed-height containers with text that could overflow when font size increases.

### 1.4.5 Images of Text
If the technologies being used can achieve the visual presentation, text must be used to convey information rather than images of text.
- Identify `<img>` elements containing photographs of text, banners with embedded text, or buttons rendered as images when CSS-styled text would suffice.

### 1.4.10 Reflow (WCAG 2.1)
Content must be presentable without loss of information or functionality and without requiring scrolling in two dimensions at 320 CSS pixels wide (for vertical content) or 256 CSS pixels tall (for horizontal content).
- Identify horizontal scrollbars at 320px viewport width caused by fixed-width layouts, `min-width` values exceeding 320px, or non-wrapping flex/grid containers.
- Identify `overflow-x: scroll` or `overflow-x: auto` on main content containers.

### 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast (WCAG 2.1)
The visual presentation of UI components and graphical objects must have a contrast ratio of at least 3:1 against adjacent colors.
- Identify form input borders, focus indicators, icon buttons, and chart elements with border/fill colors below 3:1 contrast against their background.
- Verify custom checkbox/radio/toggle visual indicators meet 3:1 contrast.
- Verify icon-only buttons have sufficient contrast.

### 1.4.12 Text Spacing (WCAG 2.1)
No loss of content or functionality must occur when users override text spacing (line height 1.5x font size, paragraph spacing 2x font size, letter spacing 0.12x font size, word spacing 0.16x font size).
- Identify fixed-height containers (`height` instead of `min-height`) that could clip text when spacing increases.
- Identify `overflow: hidden` paired with fixed dimensions that would hide text.
- Identify CSS that overrides user text spacing preferences via `!important` on `line-height`, `letter-spacing`, or `word-spacing`.

### 1.4.13 Content on Hover or Focus (WCAG 2.1)
Additional content triggered by hover or keyboard focus must be dismissible (without moving hover/focus), hoverable (pointer can move to the new content), and persistent (remains visible until dismissed or trigger is removed).
- Identify tooltips, popovers, or dropdown menus that disappear when the user tries to move the pointer to the tooltip content.
- Identify hover-triggered content without an Escape key dismissal mechanism.
- Identify CSS-only `:hover` menus that cannot be triggered via keyboard `:focus` or `:focus-within`.

## Operable

### 2.4.5 Multiple Ways
More than one way must be available to locate a web page within a set of pages.
- Verify that navigation, site search, sitemap, or table of contents mechanisms exist.

### 2.4.6 Headings and Labels
Headings and labels must describe topic or purpose.
- Identify generic headings ("Section 1", "Details", "Info") that do not describe their content.
- Identify form labels that do not describe the expected input (e.g., "Field 1" instead of "Email address").

### 2.4.7 Focus Visible
Any keyboard-operable user interface must have a mode of operation where the keyboard focus indicator is visible.
- Analyze CSS for `outline: none`, `outline: 0`, or `box-shadow: none` applied to focusable elements (`:focus`) without a visible alternative via `:focus-visible` or custom focus styling.
- Verify focus indicators have sufficient contrast (at least 3:1 against adjacent colors per WCAG 2.2 guidance).
- Verify focus indicators are visible on all interactive elements: links, buttons, inputs, selects, textareas, and custom interactive components.
- Identify `*:focus { outline: none }` global resets without corresponding `:focus-visible` replacements.

## Understandable

### 3.1.2 Language of Parts
The human language of each passage or phrase in the content must be programmatically determinable when it differs from the default page language.
- Identify inline text in a different language from the page's `lang` attribute that lacks a `lang` attribute on its container element.

### 3.2.3 Consistent Navigation
Navigational mechanisms repeated across multiple pages must occur in the same relative order each time they are repeated.
- Verify navigation menus, headers, and footers maintain the same structural order across views/routes.

### 3.2.4 Consistent Identification
Components that have the same functionality within a set of pages must be identified consistently.
- Identify the same action labeled differently across pages (e.g., "Search" on one page, "Find" on another, "Look up" on a third).

### 3.3.3 Error Suggestion
If an input error is automatically detected and suggestions for correction are known, the suggestions must be provided to the user unless it would jeopardize security or purpose.
- Identify form validation that reports errors without suggesting the expected format or valid values (e.g., "Invalid email" without "Please enter an email in the format name@example.com").

### 3.3.4 Error Prevention (Legal, Financial, Data)
For pages causing legal commitments or financial transactions, submissions must be reversible, data must be checked for errors, or a confirmation mechanism must exist.
- Identify checkout, payment, or legal agreement forms that submit without a review/confirmation step.
- Identify data deletion actions without an undo or confirmation dialog.

### 4.1.3 Status Messages (WCAG 2.1)
Status messages must be programmatically determinable through role or properties so they can be presented to the user by assistive technologies without receiving focus.
- Identify toast notifications, snackbar components, inline success/error messages, loading indicators, and search result counts that appear dynamically without `aria-live="polite"`, `aria-live="assertive"`, `role="alert"`, `role="status"`, or `role="log"`.
- Verify `aria-live` regions exist in the DOM before content is injected (late-added `aria-live` regions may not be announced).

