# Diagnostic Ruleset Matrix: WCAG 2.2 Level AA Additions

### 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum)
When a UI component receives keyboard focus, the component must not be entirely hidden by author-created content.
- Perform a cross-reference analysis of layout CSS. Identify elements utilizing `position: sticky` or `position: fixed` combined with elevated `z-index` properties.
- Verify the parent scrolling viewport container (`<html>`, `<body>`, or a designated overflow wrapper) implements `scroll-padding-top` or `scroll-padding-bottom` to prevent focused elements from being visually occluded beneath fixed overlays.
- Identify sticky headers, floating action buttons, cookie banners, or chat widgets that could cover focused elements.
- Verify that focused elements are scrolled into view and not hidden behind sticky/fixed elements.

### 2.5.7 Dragging Movements
Functionality that uses a dragging movement must also be operable by a single pointer without dragging.
- Identify drag-and-drop interfaces (sortable lists, kanban boards, file upload drop zones, range sliders) that lack a single-pointer alternative (e.g., move up/down buttons, click-to-select-and-place, typed input for range values).
- Verify custom `<input type="range">` sliders can also be operated via keyboard arrow keys and direct value input.

### 2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum)
The size of the target for pointer inputs must be at least 24x24 CSS pixels, or adequate spacing must exist so a 24px diameter circle centered on the target bounding box does not intersect another target.
- Analyze `width`, `height`, `padding`, and `min-width`/`min-height` of all interactive elements (buttons, links, form controls, custom interactive components).
- If computed visual target size falls below 24x24 CSS pixels and surrounding `margin`/`gap` is insufficient to prevent a 24px circle overlap with adjacent targets, register a violation.
- Exemptions: inline links within text blocks, user-agent default-styled controls, legally/essentially required sizes.

### 3.3.8 Accessible Authentication (Minimum)
Cognitive function tests (remembering passwords, solving puzzles, transcribing codes) must not be required for any step in an authentication process unless an alternative is provided.
- Locate all `<input type="password">` and token/OTP input elements.
- Identify event listeners that block clipboard paste operations: `onPaste={(e) => e.preventDefault()}`, `addEventListener('paste', ...)` with `preventDefault()`. Blocking paste on password/OTP fields is a critical failure.
- Verify `autocomplete` attributes are present on credential fields: `autocomplete="username"`, `autocomplete="current-password"`, `autocomplete="new-password"`, `autocomplete="one-time-code"`.
- Identify CAPTCHA implementations that rely solely on cognitive tests without an alternative (e.g., audio CAPTCHA, passkey support, or third-party authentication).

